04830nam a22006735i 9780822387831DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20062006ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223878317 a10.1515/97808223878312doi  a(DE-B1597)552205  a(OCoLC)1055300806  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aRA577.5b.M87 2006 7aMED0610002bisacsh04a613/.52221 aMurphy, Michelle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSick Building Syndrome and the Problem of Uncertainty :bEnvironmental Politics, Technoscience, and Women Workers /cMichelle Murphy. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b21 Illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Man in a Box: Building-Machines and the Science of Comfort -- t2. Building Ladies into the Office Machine -- t3. Feminism, Surveys, and Toxic Details -- t4. Indoor Pollution at the Encounter of Toxicology and Popular Epidemiology -- t5. Uncertainty, Race, and Activism at the EPA -- t6. Building Ecologies, Tobacco, and the Politics of Multiplicity -- t7. How to Build Yourself a Body in a Safe Space -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBefore 1980, sick building syndrome did not exist. By the 1990s, it was among the most commonly investigated occupational health problems in the United States. Afflicted by headaches, rashes, and immune system disorders, office workers—mostly women—protested that their workplaces were filled with toxic hazards; yet federal investigators could detect no chemical cause. This richly detailed history tells the story of how sick building syndrome came into being: how indoor exposures to chemicals wafting from synthetic carpet, ink, adhesive, solvents, and so on became something that relatively privileged Americans worried over, felt, and ultimately sought to do something about. As Michelle Murphy shows, sick building syndrome provides a window into how environmental politics moved indoors.Sick building syndrome embodied a politics of uncertainty that continues to characterize contemporary American environmental debates. Michelle Murphy explores the production of uncertainty by juxtaposing multiple histories, each of which explains how an expert or lay tradition made chemical exposures perceptible or imperceptible, existent or nonexistent. She shows how uncertainty emerged from a complex confluence of feminist activism, office worker protests, ventilation engineering, toxicology, popular epidemiology, corporate science, and ecology. In an illuminating case study, she reflects on EPA scientists’ efforts to have their headquarters recognized as a sick building. Murphy brings all of these histories together in what is not only a thorough account of an environmental health problem but also a much deeper exploration of the relationship between history, materiality, and uncertainty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAirxPollution. 0aAllergy. 0aBuildingsxHealth aspects. 0aDiseases. 0aHistory. 0aHumanities. 0aImmunologic diseases. 0aIndoor air pollutionxHealth aspects. 0aMedical care. 0aPollution. 0aPublic health. 0aSick building syndromezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSick building syndrome. 7aMEDICAL / Occupational & Industrial Medicine.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822387831zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822387831423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822387831/origi